hook.real_world_problem:
Swiggy's restaurant listing API: users browse restaurants constantly. Every page load hits PostgreSQL:

```
GET /api/restaurants?city=Hyderabad
→ SELECT * FROM restaurants WHERE city='Hyderabad' AND active=true
→ 15ms per query
→ 5,000 requests/second during dinner time
→ 5,000 × 15ms = 75 seconds of DB query time per second
→ Needs 75 concurrent DB connections just for this one endpoint!
```

**The restaurant list changes once every few hours. Why query PostgreSQL 5,000 times per second for the same data?**

```java
// BEFORE — every request hits PostgreSQL:
@GetMapping("/api/restaurants")
public List<Restaurant> getRestaurants(@RequestParam String city) {
    return restaurantRepo.findByCityAndActiveTrue(city);  // 15ms every time
}

// AFTER — Redis caches the result for 5 minutes:
@Cacheable(value = "restaurants", key = "#city")
public List<Restaurant> getRestaurants(String city) {
    return restaurantRepo.findByCityAndActiveTrue(city);
    // First call (cache miss):  15ms → stored in Redis for 5 min
    // Next 14,999 calls (hits): 0.3ms → served from Redis memory
}
```

```
Result:
  Cache hit rate: ~99% during steady state
  DB queries: 5,000/s → ~3/s (one per city per 5 minutes)
  Response time: 15ms → 0.3ms
  DB connections needed: 75 → 1
```

One annotation. Seventy-five times fewer database connections.

